@flexiarg math-strategy/characterization-result
@title Characterization-Result Family
@sigils [◇/相]
@keywords characterization, classification, dichotomy, structure, full-description, taxonomic, family-parent
@audience mathematicians, paper-writers, pattern-classifiers
@tone classification / heuristic
@factor Discernment (paññā)
@references [math-informal/exhaustion-as-theorem math-informal/structural-obstruction-as-theorem math-informal/split-into-cases math-strategy/hypothesis-category-check]

! conclusion:
  Your paper describes what some object or class of objects *is* — not whether
  one exists, not how it relates to another, but its intrinsic structure.

  + context: An object or class has been singled out, and the question is
    "what does it look like?" — exhaustively (full structural description),
    partially (where it fails some property), in cases (classification), or in
    a sharp regime split (dichotomy).

  + IF:
      The paper's main contribution can be expressed as "we describe completely
      the structure of X", or "we classify all instances of X", or "we exhibit
      the regime where X fails property P", or "we show X belongs to one of
      two regimes".

  + HOWEVER:
      Characterization is the most populous family in mathematical literature
      (≈ 33 % of papers in our pilot — see
      `futon3/holes/excursions/E-math-prototype-pilot.md` Phase 2). Within it,
      the leaves diverge sharply: full-characterization is positive structural
      content; failure-mode is "where this fails"; classification lists cases;
      dichotomy is the special case of classification with two regimes. The
      analytic moves needed for each leaf are different.

  + THEN:
      1. Decide whether the paper aims at full description, partial / failure
         description, an enumeration of cases, or a binary regime split.
      2. Pick the matching leaf member-pattern.
      3. Identify the *witness* of the characterization: what theorem,
         equivalence, or list constitutes the description?

  + BECAUSE:
      Characterization papers do "describing-work" rather than "proving-X-exists"
      or "showing-X-relates-to-Y" work. The family parent serves as a coarse
      classifier; the leaves carry the analytic differences (e.g. dichotomy
      proofs almost always need a phase-transition argument; classification
      proofs need exhaustion).

  + MEMBER-PATTERNS:
      member[math-informal/exhaustion-as-theorem]                 # full / classification
      member[math-informal/structural-obstruction-as-theorem]     # failure-mode
      member[math-informal/split-into-cases]                      # dichotomy / classification
      member[math-informal/structural-characterization]           # full description (new leaf)
      member[math-informal/failure-mode-characterization]         # failure-regime (new leaf)
      member[math-informal/complexity-classification]             # specific subtype (new leaf)

  + EXEMPLAR-PAPERS:
      exemplar[arxiv-2604.20815v1]   # Zarankiewicz sharp dichotomy
      exemplar[arxiv-2604.20827v1]   # Entropic OT failure-mode
      exemplar[arxiv-2604.20787v1]   # Exchange-number complexity
      exemplar[arxiv-math/0603592v1] # KMS classification
      exemplar[arxiv-math/0603593v1] # AFD outer-actions classification

  + NEXT-STEPS:
      next[Decide whether the characterization is full, partial / failure-mode, classification, or dichotomy.]
      next[Identify the witness — list, theorem, equivalence — that constitutes the description.]
      next[Cross-check: does the paper *prove the characterization is exhaustive*, or only *exhibit examples*?]
